New rules for the global economy.
CAMBRIDGE, MASS.: Let's assume the world's top politicians would gather again in Bretton Woods, New Hampshire, to design a new world economic order.
They would, of course, focus above all on today's problems: the crisis of the eurozone, global recovery, financial regulation, international macroeconomic imbalances, etc. But dealing with these questions would force the assembled leaders to move beyond that and reconsider the solidity of the global economic arrangements as a whole.
Here are seven principles for global economic governance based on sound human reason, on which they might possibly agree.
(I discuss this in greater detail in my new book, The Globalization Paradox.)
The markets must be deeply embedded in the existing control systems.
The notion that markets regulate themselves has suffered a mortal blow in the recent financial crisis and should be buried once and for all.
Markets need other social institutions to support them.
They rely on courts, legal systems, and regulatory agencies to establish and enforce rules.
They are dependent on stabilization functions offered by central banks and countercyclical fiscal policy.
They need the political acceptance generated by redistributive taxation, safety nets, and social insurance.
And all of this applies equally to global markets.
For the foreseeable future, a democratic state leadership is likely to be organized to a large extent within national political communities.
The national state lives, even if it may falter a bit, and remains essentially the only game in town.
The pursuit of a world government is a futile endeavor.
It is hardly to be expected that national governments will relinquish significant control to transnational institutions; in addition, harmonizing rules would be of no use to societies with different needs and preferences.
The European Union could be the only exception to this axiom, although its current crisis seems to prove the opposite.
We waste international cooperation on overly ambitious goals far too often. Ultimately, weak results emerge, representing the lowest common denominator between the major countries.
When international cooperation is "successful," it yields rules that are either toothless or reflect the preferences of the more powerful countries.
The Basel regulations on capital requirements and the rules of the World Trade Organization on subsidies, intellectual property, and investment measures typify this form of excessive zeal.
We can strengthen the efficiency and legitimacy of globalisation by supporting democratic procedures in our own country, rather than destroying them.
