3. Pluralist Economic Prosperity: The admission that the central institutional infrastructure of the global economy must be built on a national level gives individual countries the freedom to develop institutions that best suit their needs.
The US, Europe, and Japan have produced comparable prosperity in the long term.
However, their labor markets, company regulation, cartel guidelines, social security, and financial systems differ significantly, and a sequence of these "models" – another one in each decade – is then presented as the great success that one should emulate.
The most successful societies of the future will make room for experiments and allow for further evolution of their institutions.
A world economy that recognizes the need and value of institutional diversity will foster such experimentalism and evolutionary development rather than suppress it.
4. Countries have the right to protect their own rules and institutions.
The aforementioned principles may appear unobjectionable.
But they carry powerful implications that collide with the prevailing opinion of globalization proponents.
Such an implication is the right of individual countries to protect their national institutional decisions.
The recognition of institutional diversity would be meaningless if countries did not have the instruments available to shape and preserve their own institutions – in a word: to "protect".
We should therefore accept that countries retain national rules – tax policy, financial regulation, labor standards or rules for consumer health and safety – and that they are entitled to do so by possibly building restrictions at their borders if trade is proven to threaten domestic practices that enjoy broad support among the population.
Proponents of globalization are right; calls for such protection measures will fail for lack of evidence or support.
If they are in conflict, there is a safeguard to ensure that both the benefits of open economies and the benefits of retaining national regulations are given a fair hearing in public debates.
Five countries have no right to impose their own institutions on others.
The use of restrictions in cross-border trade or in the financial sector to maintain values and rules in one's own country is not to be confused with using them to impose these values and rules on other countries.
The rules of globalization should not force Americans or Europeans to consume goods produced in a way that most citizens in these countries find unacceptable.
They should not allow the US or the EU to impose trade sanctions or other pressure mechanisms to change labor market rules, environmental policy, or financial regulation of other countries.
Countries have a right to diversity, not to forced convergence.
