6. International agreements on economic regulation for the interaction between national institutions: Relying on national states to provide the fundamental control functions of the global economy does not mean that we should dispense with international rules.
The Bretton Woods system also had clear rules, even if they were limited in scope and depth.
A total Catch-as-catch-can would be of no use to anyone.
What we need are traffic rules for the global economy that help vehicles of different size, shape, and speed navigate around each other, rather than prescribing identical cars or a uniform speed limit.
We should strive for a maximum degree of globalisation that is in line with preserving the space for diversity within national institutional arrangements.
7. Undemocratic countries can't rely on the same rights and privileges in the international economic order as democracies.
What lends the aforementioned principles their attractiveness and legitimacy is that they are based on democratic consultation – where this actually takes place, within the nation-states.
If states are not democratic, this framework collapses.
We can no longer assume that their institutional arrangements reflect the preferences of their citizens.
For undemocratic states, therefore, other, less liberal rules must apply.
These are the principles that architects of the next world economic order must accept.
What's most important in this case is that they have to accept the ultimate paradox that each of these principles illustrates: Globalization works best when you don't push it too far.
